<HEADLINE>
<P>
'DETOX CENTERS' FOR 'ELECTRICAL ABUSE'? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your article on use of electrical stimulation to relax seemed too good to be 
true. Maybe it is ("Getting Wired for Relaxation," March 6). 
</P>
<P>
A couple of questions come to mind. What does electrical stimulation 
chronically do to the body? Will we be developing a generation of electrical 
junkies who require a 20-minute zap to feel their best? Already, one week after 
Cloris Leachman purchased an Alpha-Stim unit, she "won't leave home without" 
it. Will there be a rebound loss in one's normal alpha state when the 
artificial stimulation is discontinued? 
</P>
<P>
Please note that the units are FDA approved for pain relief, not relaxation. 
</P>
<P>
Hopefully, these questions will be answered before usage becomes commonplace. I 
can already envision commercials for detox centers to treat electrical abuse. 
</P>
<P>
DR. ROBERT W. EITCHES, Beverly Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
