<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK'S FILM PICKS BY THE CRITICS: MARRIED TO THE MOB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In this hilarious and stylish 1988 Jonathan Demme comedy, Mafia widow Michelle 
Pfeiffer finds herself on the run, pursued by Dean Stockwell's lecherous don 
and aided, more or less, by Matthew Modine's sweetly square FBI agent. 
</P>
<P>
Sunday 5 p.m. TMC 
</P>
<P>
The Postman Always Rings Twice 
</P>
<P>
This is the steamy, guilt-ridden 1946 Tay Garnett version with Lana Turner, 
always in white, most memorably in a two-piece bathing suit, and John Garfield. 
</P>
<P>
Wednesday 10 a.m. KCOP 
</P>
<P>
Some Like It Hot 
</P>
<P>
Billy Wilder's 1959 classic may just be the funniest movie since the advent of 
sound. Jack Lemmon and Tony Curtis are Chicago musicians who have the bad luck 
to witness the St. Valentine Day's Massacre and wind up in drag with an 
all-girl band heading for Miami. Its vocalist is, of course, Marilyn Monroe. 
</P>
<P>
Wednesday 8 p.m. KTTV 
</P>
<P>
Seven Samurai 
</P>
<P>
The great 1954 Akira Kurosawa classic stars Toshiro Mifune as one of seven 
samurai hired by a small village to protect it from bandits. For all its 
innovative and dynamic battle scenes, it is a richly contemplative, reflective 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
Friday 9 p.m. KCET Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</TEXT>
